  "prompt": "What is the difference between wires and cables?",
  "response": "Wires and cables are often used interchangeably, but they have distinct differences:\n\n1. **Wire:**\n   - **Definition:** A wire is a single, usually cylindrical, strand or rod of metal. Wires can also be made up of strands that are twisted or braided together (stranded wire).\n   - **Construction:** Typically consists of a single conductor, although, in the case of stranded wire, it\u2019s multiple strands twisted together to form a single wire.\n   - **Usage:** Used primarily for the conduction of electricity or telecommunications signals. They are often used in internal circuits or for connections within devices.\n   - **Insulation:** May be bare or insulated. If insulated, it usually has a single layer of insulation material.\n\n2. **Cable:**\n   - **Definition:** A cable consists of two or more wires that are bound together. Cables are typically grouped in a protective sheathing.\n   - **Construction:** Made up of multiple conductors (wires), which may have additional layers of insulation, armor, and shielding.\n   - **Usage:** Used for transmitting electricity, telecommunications signals, or both, over longer distances. They are used in power distribution and telecommunications.\n   - **Insulation and Sheathing:** Has multiple layers of insulation, which can also include shielding and protective outer sheathing. This makes cables more robust and suitable for a variety of environments.\n\nIn summary, wires are single conductors (which can be solid or stranded), while cables are assemblies of multiple wires, which are often insulated for additional protection and reinforced with shielding or armor for enhanced durability and protection.",
